00:02:10.244 --> 00:02:12.106
- That's kind of a
gruesome picture, isn't it?

00:02:12.106 --> 00:02:16.031
But I like to imagine Darwin
in the dissecting room,

00:02:16.031 --> 00:02:18.603
actually helping us all out.

00:02:18.603 --> 00:02:20.996
So this is a lecture that's
an experiment for me.

00:02:20.996 --> 00:02:21.831
It's shifting the focus.

00:02:21.831 --> 00:02:24.117
All of my previous lectures
about evolution and medicine

00:02:24.117 --> 00:02:26.255
have been about traits, things like height

00:02:26.255 --> 00:02:28.779
and pneumonia and cancer and all the rest.

00:02:28.779 --> 00:02:31.150
Today, I'm gonna shift
gears and try to apply

00:02:31.150 --> 00:02:33.279
the things we've learned
about how to analyze

00:02:33.279 --> 00:02:36.556
why traits are vulnerable
to disease, and ask instead

00:02:36.556 --> 00:02:40.408
why genes that cause disease
persist in the genome,

00:02:40.408 --> 00:02:43.088
despite the actions of natural selection.

00:02:43.088 --> 00:02:44.943
Evolutionary medicine,
just to be very clear,

00:02:44.943 --> 00:02:47.219
is not a specialized method of practice.

00:02:47.219 --> 00:02:49.407
There's nothing alternative
about it whatsoever.

00:02:49.407 --> 00:02:52.182
It's simply applying the
well-established basic principles

00:02:52.182 --> 00:02:55.368
from evolutionary biology to
medicine and public health

00:02:55.368 --> 00:02:58.296
and trying to use them
to improve human health.

00:02:58.296 --> 00:03:00.272
So the central question
I've been preoccupied by is

00:03:00.272 --> 00:03:01.838
why do bodies have traits

00:03:01.838 --> 00:03:03.959
that make them vulnerable to disease?

00:03:03.959 --> 00:03:04.792
Completely different from

00:03:04.792 --> 00:03:06.912
the usual medical research question.

00:03:06.912 --> 00:03:10.269
Most medical research is about
why people are different.

00:03:10.269 --> 00:03:13.213
Our interest is instead
about why we are all the same

00:03:13.213 --> 00:03:17.380
in ways that are kind of like
the gas tank on the Pinto.

00:03:18.256 --> 00:03:20.315
There are things about our bodies,

00:03:20.315 --> 00:03:21.789
from our backs to our appendices.

00:03:21.789 --> 00:03:23.983
Well, we'll get to that in a moment.

00:03:23.983 --> 00:03:25.454
The first half of medical school,

00:03:25.454 --> 00:03:29.960
you must react with awe if
you're paying attention at all.

00:03:29.960 --> 00:03:32.703
The Loop of Henle in the
kidney, no details now,

00:03:32.703 --> 00:03:34.633
but, oh, my gosh, if you're not astounded,

00:03:34.633 --> 00:03:36.243
you're not paying attention.

00:03:36.243 --> 00:03:39.155
Everybody recognizes
how great the heart is

00:03:39.155 --> 00:03:41.286
and the valves in the right
place at the right time,

00:03:41.286 --> 00:03:44.049
and the pump does not need
to be oiled every few months.

00:03:44.049 --> 00:03:48.959
The eye is miraculous in the
fact of its astounding function

00:03:48.959 --> 00:03:51.727
although it's actually not well-designed.

00:03:51.727 --> 00:03:54.233
The human hand is almost equally good

00:03:54.233 --> 00:03:57.443
in terms of all of those
muscles and tendons and joints

00:03:57.443 --> 00:04:01.949
working in tandem to allow
us to do amazing things.

00:04:01.949 --> 00:04:05.088
The clotting mechanism had
better work well or else,

00:04:05.088 --> 00:04:07.418
and then the part of
biology that I thought

00:04:07.418 --> 00:04:10.238
was absolutely ridiculous and stupid

00:04:10.238 --> 00:04:12.927
and at least made me mad
when I was a medical student,

00:04:12.927 --> 00:04:15.184
and now I find fascinating
because I've taken

00:04:15.184 --> 00:04:17.971
an evolutionary viewpoint, is biochemistry

00:04:17.971 --> 00:04:19.580
and intermediary metabolism.

00:04:19.580 --> 00:04:21.577
(audience laughing)

00:04:21.577 --> 00:04:23.162
For any students in the
audience, I assure you,

00:04:23.162 --> 00:04:25.050
don't pay attention to your professors.

00:04:25.050 --> 00:04:26.999
Go to evolutionary
thinking about these things

00:04:26.999 --> 00:04:27.969
and it will make sense.

00:04:27.969 --> 00:04:29.541
That's the first half of medical school.

00:04:29.541 --> 00:04:31.592
Second half, you get into the
clinic and what do you see?

00:04:31.592 --> 00:04:33.172
Somebody goofed.

00:04:33.172 --> 00:04:36.465
You start off with wisdom teeth, why?

00:04:36.465 --> 00:04:39.538
You go further to the appendix, whoa!

00:04:39.538 --> 00:04:41.408
You go further to the place in your arm

00:04:41.408 --> 00:04:43.853
that always breaks when you fall forward?

00:04:43.853 --> 00:04:44.959
Why isn't it bigger?

00:04:44.959 --> 00:04:46.743
The coronary arteries,
couldn't they just be

00:04:46.743 --> 00:04:48.916
a little bit wider, please?

00:04:48.916 --> 00:04:51.381
And as for that birth
canal, why not just have

00:04:51.381 --> 00:04:53.593
a zipper in the front instead of...

00:04:53.593 --> 00:04:55.501
(audience laughing)

00:04:55.501 --> 00:04:57.986
And then there's the spine,
as I mentioned before.

00:04:57.986 --> 00:04:59.592
The body could be so much better

00:04:59.592 --> 00:05:00.495
in so many different ways.

00:05:00.495 --> 00:05:03.357
These are traits, not genes, just traits,

00:05:03.357 --> 00:05:05.669
and the old answer about
why natural selection

00:05:05.669 --> 00:05:07.833
didn't do a better job is, well,

00:05:07.833 --> 00:05:10.288
it's a random process
and it's not that strong.

00:05:10.288 --> 00:05:13.472
That is absolutely one
important contribution

00:05:13.472 --> 00:05:16.142
to why bodies aren't
better, but it's only one,

00:05:16.142 --> 00:05:19.292
and a foundation for
evolutionary thinking in medicine

00:05:19.292 --> 00:05:20.560
has been to analyze

00:05:20.560 --> 00:05:22.773
every kind of vulnerability of a trait

00:05:22.773 --> 00:05:26.259
in terms of six possible
different evolutionary reasons

00:05:26.259 --> 00:05:28.009
why we're vulnerable.

00:05:28.883 --> 00:05:30.363
I'm going to list them very quickly.

00:05:30.363 --> 00:05:32.103
I've given many, many lectures about these

00:05:32.103 --> 00:05:34.742
applying to traits, they're on
the web if you're interested.

00:05:34.742 --> 00:05:37.779
Today, I'm gonna zip through
them and apply them to genes.

00:05:37.779 --> 00:05:40.477
One is natural selection just can't do it.

00:05:40.477 --> 00:05:42.192
Two is we're living in an environment

00:05:42.192 --> 00:05:45.434
very different from the
environment in which we evolved.

00:05:45.434 --> 00:05:47.495
Three is that pathogens,
bacteria and viruses

00:05:47.495 --> 00:05:50.040
evolve faster than we do.

00:05:50.040 --> 00:05:52.149
Four is trade-offs;
nothing can be perfect.

00:05:52.149 --> 00:05:54.361
Everything can be adjusted
in ways that are better

00:05:54.361 --> 00:05:57.088
but at the cost of making
something else worse.

00:05:57.088 --> 00:05:59.327
Five, and this is a deep one,

00:05:59.327 --> 00:06:02.391
natural selection does not
shape any organism for health

00:06:02.391 --> 00:06:04.725
or longevity or happiness or cooperation.

00:06:04.725 --> 00:06:07.093
It shapes all of them for maximizing

00:06:07.093 --> 00:06:09.244
their ability to transmit their genes.

00:06:09.244 --> 00:06:10.859
Very disturbing idea.

00:06:10.859 --> 00:06:13.876
The last is useful defenses
that seem like diseases,

00:06:13.876 --> 00:06:16.014
such as fever, pain, nausea,

00:06:16.014 --> 00:06:18.779
vomiting, cough and all the rest.

00:06:18.779 --> 00:06:21.074
Now, I'm gonna shift though, my usual talk

00:06:21.074 --> 00:06:24.589
and give up on talking about
traits, and ask about genes,

00:06:24.589 --> 00:06:26.998
the focus of so much modern
medical research, and ask,

00:06:26.998 --> 00:06:31.743
why do genes that increase
risk of disease persist?

00:06:31.743 --> 00:06:34.638
And the first thing I recognized
as I started down this path

00:06:34.638 --> 00:06:37.391
is that we don't need to just
talk about the usual foci

00:06:37.391 --> 00:06:40.984
of medical research,
which are the myriad kinds

00:06:40.984 --> 00:06:42.746
of specific variations in genes

00:06:42.746 --> 00:06:44.609
that make us vulnerable to disease.

00:06:44.609 --> 00:06:46.159
We also need to talk about genes

00:06:46.159 --> 00:06:49.386
that we all share, that are fixed,

00:06:49.386 --> 00:06:51.116
fixed means we all have it,

00:06:51.116 --> 00:06:53.504
that make us vulnerable to disease.

00:06:53.504 --> 00:06:55.076
This led me to just say
there's four different kinds

00:06:55.076 --> 00:06:56.892
of genes we should be thinking about.

00:06:56.892 --> 00:06:59.621
First are the regular
ones, widespread variation,

00:06:59.621 --> 00:07:02.232
all the regular genetic studies.

00:07:02.232 --> 00:07:05.091
Two, variation between populations.

00:07:05.091 --> 00:07:08.478
DARC is a gene that almost
everyone in Africa has

00:07:08.478 --> 00:07:10.794
because it protects against vivax malaria.

00:07:10.794 --> 00:07:14.362
Hardly anyone living in
northern climates has this gene.

00:07:14.362 --> 00:07:16.769
Fixed or missing genes
for everybody recently.

00:07:16.769 --> 00:07:19.492
Recently, the past few million years.

00:07:19.492 --> 00:07:24.230
The one that Ajit Varki
studies, Neu5Gc and GLO,

00:07:24.230 --> 00:07:26.199
more about those in just a moment.

00:07:26.199 --> 00:07:29.188
The fourth category is
genes that we all have,

00:07:29.188 --> 00:07:32.151
such as genes that make bilirubin,

00:07:32.151 --> 00:07:35.317
and genes that make dopamine,

00:07:35.317 --> 00:07:37.880
all of which make us
vulnerable to disease.

00:07:37.880 --> 00:07:39.892
So, a big shift in thinking
here, not just variations

00:07:39.892 --> 00:07:42.298
among individuals and
their different genes,

00:07:42.298 --> 00:07:44.051
but genes that we all have

00:07:44.051 --> 00:07:46.080
that make us vulnerable to disease.

00:07:46.080 --> 00:07:48.056
The first reason, limits of selection.

00:07:48.056 --> 00:07:49.741
Selection can't do things,

00:07:49.741 --> 00:07:54.154
and the biggest limit to
selection is mutations happen.

00:07:54.154 --> 00:07:58.552
About 60 to 130 per
individual per generation,

00:07:58.552 --> 00:08:00.923
and a deep question for another time is

00:08:00.923 --> 00:08:03.465
how on earth the genome
can fail to melt down

00:08:03.465 --> 00:08:06.045
given the difficulty of
getting rid of each of those,

00:08:06.045 --> 00:08:07.614
but they are all gradually

00:08:07.614 --> 00:08:09.874
selected out by natural selection,

00:08:09.874 --> 00:08:13.139
except that natural selection's
by no means all powerful.

00:08:13.139 --> 00:08:15.472
There's something that
geneticists call drift,

00:08:15.472 --> 00:08:17.204
which is really referring
to random factors

00:08:17.204 --> 00:08:19.900
that make genes become more or less common

00:08:19.900 --> 00:08:21.901
just by luck of the draw,

00:08:21.901 --> 00:08:23.500
not because of anything pushing them

00:08:23.500 --> 00:08:25.944
to higher or lower frequencies.

00:08:25.944 --> 00:08:28.148
This can result in good genes being lost

00:08:28.148 --> 00:08:30.963
and good genes becoming more common.

00:08:30.963 --> 00:08:33.565
Here is the biggest question that faces us

00:08:33.565 --> 00:08:35.259
in medical genetics today.

00:08:35.259 --> 00:08:38.098
We all thought, just about 15 years ago,

00:08:38.098 --> 00:08:39.926
that the highly heritable diseases,

00:08:39.926 --> 00:08:42.864
such as schizophrenia,
autism, bipolar disease,

00:08:42.864 --> 00:08:45.265
and things like diabetes and all the rest,

00:08:45.265 --> 00:08:46.913
that they were highly heritable,

00:08:46.913 --> 00:08:49.552
we know their variation in these diseases

00:08:49.552 --> 00:08:51.146
is caused by genetic variations,

00:08:51.146 --> 00:08:53.547
so we should be able to find the genes

00:08:53.547 --> 00:08:55.188
and fix these diseases.

00:08:55.188 --> 00:08:56.427
This has been one of the greatest

00:08:56.427 --> 00:08:58.744
disappointments in modern medicine.

00:08:58.744 --> 00:09:00.226
We're making some progress, but,

00:09:00.226 --> 00:09:02.143
it was a huge disappointment.

00:09:02.143 --> 00:09:05.728
This is a graph done by
one of my former students

00:09:05.728 --> 00:09:08.447
in this college looking at
genes for schizophrenia.

00:09:08.447 --> 00:09:09.811
I say genes, what I really mean,

00:09:09.811 --> 00:09:11.772
for the technically inclined, is alleles.

00:09:11.772 --> 00:09:13.224
That is, different variations

00:09:13.224 --> 00:09:17.174
that influence risk of
something like schizophrenia.

00:09:17.174 --> 00:09:20.508
These are ones that are
relatively uncommon,

00:09:20.508 --> 00:09:22.568
and they have relatively large effects.

00:09:22.568 --> 00:09:24.124
Increase in the risk of schizophrenia

00:09:24.124 --> 00:09:26.138
by as much as five to 10 times,

00:09:26.138 --> 00:09:28.586
but they're very, very rare.

00:09:28.586 --> 00:09:31.561
These re alleles that
are relatively common,

00:09:31.561 --> 00:09:33.595
and their effect on schizophrenia

00:09:33.595 --> 00:09:35.368
is really quite tiny.

00:09:35.368 --> 00:09:39.221
They increase the risk by 1% or 2% or 3%.

00:09:39.221 --> 00:09:42.927
Notice that they all
fall on the same line.

00:09:42.927 --> 00:09:46.048
Notice next that there
are no genes over there.

00:09:46.048 --> 00:09:46.881
There are no effects.

00:09:46.881 --> 00:09:50.042
There are no common genes of large effect.

00:09:50.042 --> 00:09:51.506
What happened to them?

00:09:51.506 --> 00:09:55.635
Natural selection eliminated
them is the main hypothesis.

00:09:55.635 --> 00:09:57.998
But, more important here,

00:09:57.998 --> 00:10:00.825
all of these genes have the exact same

00:10:00.825 --> 00:10:03.201
proportion of variants explained,

00:10:03.201 --> 00:10:07.017
and the data proportion
of variants is 0.04%,

00:10:07.017 --> 00:10:11.288
which is a teensy, teensy,
teensy amount of explanation.

00:10:11.288 --> 00:10:12.715
This has been terribly frustrating.

00:10:12.715 --> 00:10:17.011
A gene that causes less than 5% of 5%

00:10:17.011 --> 00:10:19.049
is not gonna get you very far in terms of

00:10:19.049 --> 00:10:20.987
explaining these diseases.

00:10:20.987 --> 00:10:22.516
Sickle Cell Disease has been the exemplar

00:10:22.516 --> 00:10:23.731
for evolutionary medicine,

00:10:23.731 --> 00:10:26.827
but I'd like to suggest to
you, it's a very poor exemplar.

00:10:26.827 --> 00:10:29.012
It's interesting, because of the mechanism

00:10:29.012 --> 00:10:32.508
that maintains the
frequency of the alleles

00:10:32.508 --> 00:10:34.935
that cause Sickle Cell Disease.

00:10:34.935 --> 00:10:36.481
It was first discovered, actually, in part

00:10:36.481 --> 00:10:38.389
by colleagues of mine at Michigan,

00:10:38.389 --> 00:10:39.825
Jim Neil and his colleagues,

00:10:39.825 --> 00:10:41.415
and they pointed out that

00:10:41.415 --> 00:10:42.298
when they went to Africa and looked at

00:10:42.298 --> 00:10:44.926
the distribution of malaria

00:10:44.926 --> 00:10:47.691
and the distribution
of Sickle Cell Disease,

00:10:47.691 --> 00:10:50.087
it was about the same.

00:10:50.087 --> 00:10:51.222
And, then they thought about it

00:10:51.222 --> 00:10:52.935
more deeply in a genetic way,

00:10:52.935 --> 00:10:54.993
and recognized something that's called

00:10:54.993 --> 00:10:57.457
balancing selection, this maintains

00:10:57.457 --> 00:11:00.953
the frequency of the alleles
that cause Sickle Cell Disease.

00:11:00.953 --> 00:11:02.219
You have to have two of them

00:11:02.219 --> 00:11:05.242
to get the Sickle Cell Disease
at a certain frequency.

00:11:05.242 --> 00:11:07.913
If you have two regular hemoglobin copies,

00:11:07.913 --> 00:11:09.681
you're vulnerable to Malaria,

00:11:09.681 --> 00:11:11.621
but you don't get Sickle Cell Disease.

00:11:11.621 --> 00:11:14.456
If you have two of the Sickle
Cell kinds of hemoglobin,

00:11:14.456 --> 00:11:17.067
you get severe disease, often dying young,

00:11:17.067 --> 00:11:19.481
and usually not being able to reproduce.

00:11:19.481 --> 00:11:21.249
But, if you have one of each,

00:11:21.249 --> 00:11:24.393
and you're living in Africa
where the malaria is common,

00:11:24.393 --> 00:11:26.355
or around the Mediterranean,
where it's common,

00:11:26.355 --> 00:11:28.491
it's not just Africa,

00:11:28.491 --> 00:11:30.149
you get some malaria protection,

00:11:30.149 --> 00:11:32.052
and the anemia is not too severe.

00:11:32.052 --> 00:11:33.538
These people do better in terms of

00:11:33.538 --> 00:11:36.403
having more offspring than these or these,

00:11:36.403 --> 00:11:39.693
and this means that, so long
as that gene isn't too common,

00:11:39.693 --> 00:11:41.327
if it gets too common then a lot of people

00:11:41.327 --> 00:11:42.953
get two copies, and it's terrible.

00:11:42.953 --> 00:11:46.318
If it's really rare, no
benefit, but middle range.

00:11:46.318 --> 00:11:50.404
Fascinating example, but
again, it's not a great example

00:11:50.404 --> 00:11:52.512
because what natural selection

00:11:52.512 --> 00:11:54.208
does when these kind of things happen

00:11:54.208 --> 00:11:56.120
is find some other solution.

00:11:56.120 --> 00:11:58.990
This has only been going
on for 10 to 20,000 years,

00:11:58.990 --> 00:12:00.859
and we don't have very many other examples

00:12:00.859 --> 00:12:02.484
of balancing selection.

00:12:02.484 --> 00:12:04.544
I say this because so
many of my colleagues,

00:12:04.544 --> 00:12:05.756
especially in psychiatry,

00:12:05.756 --> 00:12:09.224
are constantly making up
stories about possible traits,

00:12:09.224 --> 00:12:10.331
like schizophrenia for instance,

00:12:10.331 --> 00:12:12.223
resulting from heterozygote advantage

00:12:12.223 --> 00:12:13.524
or balancing selection.

00:12:13.524 --> 00:12:15.328
Usually, not much evidence for that

00:12:15.328 --> 00:12:18.360
except for other kinds
of hemoglobinopathies

00:12:18.360 --> 00:12:19.872
to protect against malaria.

00:12:19.872 --> 00:12:22.434
There are a few others, but
it's not a common explanation,

00:12:22.434 --> 00:12:24.150
shouldn't be the exemplar.

00:12:24.150 --> 00:12:25.497
Something that should be, though,

00:12:25.497 --> 00:12:26.667
is something like dopamine.

00:12:26.667 --> 00:12:28.045
You probably are all aware that

00:12:28.045 --> 00:12:30.842
dopamine in the substantia
nigra in the brain,

00:12:30.842 --> 00:12:33.570
in basal ganglia, if you
don't have enough of it,

00:12:33.570 --> 00:12:36.478
and your neurons are dying off,
you get Parkinson's Disease.

00:12:36.478 --> 00:12:37.602
It's common.

00:12:37.602 --> 00:12:39.687
Why are we vulnerable
to Parkinson's Disease?

00:12:39.687 --> 00:12:41.725
Well, turns out that it's inherent

00:12:41.725 --> 00:12:43.931
to the nature of the dopamine molecule.

00:12:43.931 --> 00:12:46.552
When it's metabolized,
the dopamine molecule

00:12:46.552 --> 00:12:49.766
makes hydrogen peroxide
and other oxygen radicals.

00:12:49.766 --> 00:12:51.012
These things, whenever they

00:12:51.012 --> 00:12:53.866
glom onto a piece of
tissue, fry it, essentially.

00:12:53.866 --> 00:12:56.794
Dopamine is an inherently toxic molecule,

00:12:56.794 --> 00:12:59.031
and we're not gonna be able to replace it,

00:12:59.031 --> 00:13:00.511
because it's been used to regulate

00:13:00.511 --> 00:13:03.210
motivation systems for
about a billion years, now.

00:13:03.210 --> 00:13:05.139
No chance of changing that,

00:13:05.139 --> 00:13:06.941
but it's also inherently dangerous.

00:13:06.941 --> 00:13:08.563
There are built in protection mechanisms

00:13:08.563 --> 00:13:10.018
in those nerves to protect them

00:13:10.018 --> 00:13:11.449
against the effects of dopamine,

00:13:11.449 --> 00:13:13.438
and if those aren't working quite right

00:13:13.438 --> 00:13:16.487
for one reason or another,
people get Parkinson's Disease.

00:13:16.487 --> 00:13:20.139
Second explanation, mismatch
with the environment.

00:13:20.139 --> 00:13:21.291
We used to think that common diseases

00:13:21.291 --> 00:13:24.447
were caused by common genes,
and we would find them.

00:13:24.447 --> 00:13:26.271
But, that turned out not to be the case.

00:13:26.271 --> 00:13:28.398
Hardly any common diseases are caused by

00:13:28.398 --> 00:13:31.114
common genes that are large effects.

00:13:31.114 --> 00:13:33.788
Most disease genes that have large effects

00:13:33.788 --> 00:13:37.024
are what George Williams
and I have called quirks.

00:13:37.024 --> 00:13:38.791
Quirks are not defective,

00:13:38.791 --> 00:13:40.829
they're genes that have bad effects

00:13:40.829 --> 00:13:43.162
only in modern environments.

00:13:44.241 --> 00:13:46.097
This leads to the paradoxical finding that

00:13:46.097 --> 00:13:47.660
most highly heritable diseases

00:13:47.660 --> 00:13:50.296
are caused by the environment.

00:13:50.296 --> 00:13:51.833
Doesn't that sound odd?

00:13:51.833 --> 00:13:53.529
Quirks, harmless in a natural environment,

00:13:53.529 --> 00:13:55.385
cause disease in novel environment,

00:13:55.385 --> 00:13:57.035
Ken Weiss, a geneticist, says

00:13:57.035 --> 00:13:59.600
a widespread dispersion of
these common risk alleles,

00:13:59.600 --> 00:14:02.873
they're benign, the proofs are benign,

00:14:02.873 --> 00:14:04.596
so if they're associated with disease,

00:14:04.596 --> 00:14:06.739
this mans that they're interacting

00:14:06.739 --> 00:14:09.289
with modern environments
to causing disease,

00:14:09.289 --> 00:14:11.503
pointing the finger to the environment.

00:14:11.503 --> 00:14:13.314
So next time the New York Times says,

00:14:13.314 --> 00:14:16.481
"We found a gene for atherosclerosis,"

00:14:17.616 --> 00:14:20.269
it's probably a gene
that didn't do much harm

00:14:20.269 --> 00:14:22.273
back in the environments with the sort

00:14:22.273 --> 00:14:23.794
that Mike Gurven was studying.

00:14:23.794 --> 00:14:25.247
It's a gene that interacts with Big Macs

00:14:25.247 --> 00:14:27.535
to cause heart attacks.

00:14:27.535 --> 00:14:30.635
Nearsightedness, whether
you're nearsighted or not

00:14:30.635 --> 00:14:33.308
depends almost entirely on your genes.

00:14:33.308 --> 00:14:35.308
So why didn't natural
selection get rid of them?

00:14:35.308 --> 00:14:37.134
Answer, hardly anyone is

00:14:37.134 --> 00:14:39.863
nearsighted in ancestral environments.

00:14:39.863 --> 00:14:42.128
Something about modern
environments boosts the rate

00:14:42.128 --> 00:14:45.280
so that everybody that has
those genes gets nearsighted.

00:14:45.280 --> 00:14:47.330
Three candidates for that,

00:14:47.330 --> 00:14:51.250
one is doing close work,
two is high doses of sugar,

00:14:51.250 --> 00:14:53.926
three, low levels of light
because of living indoors.

00:14:53.926 --> 00:14:56.447
Yet, to discover exactly what this is,

00:14:56.447 --> 00:14:59.625
we could eventually cure
or prevent nearsightedness

00:14:59.625 --> 00:15:01.432
if we could find the answer.

00:15:01.432 --> 00:15:04.697
Scurvy, our ancestors didn't have scurvy

00:15:04.697 --> 00:15:06.570
because they made their own,

00:15:06.570 --> 00:15:09.826
ancestors back a few million years,

00:15:09.826 --> 00:15:11.507
they made their own Vitamin C.

00:15:11.507 --> 00:15:13.729
But, we lost the ability
to make Vitamin C,

00:15:13.729 --> 00:15:15.975
and we lost it right about here.

00:15:15.975 --> 00:15:18.195
All the monkeys, marmosets, and humans,

00:15:18.195 --> 00:15:19.672
and gorillas, we can't make it.

00:15:19.672 --> 00:15:21.877
Lemurs and others can.

00:15:21.877 --> 00:15:24.138
Why did that ability get lost?

00:15:24.138 --> 00:15:26.368
One hypothesis has been
that it's just because

00:15:26.368 --> 00:15:29.162
we had so much fruit in
our diet, it didn't matter.

00:15:29.162 --> 00:15:30.962
That's a perfectly plausible one,

00:15:30.962 --> 00:15:32.594
but other people have suggested that

00:15:32.594 --> 00:15:34.944
changes in this particular enzyme

00:15:34.944 --> 00:15:37.537
increase our ability to store fats.

00:15:37.537 --> 00:15:40.008
Very interesting to try
to answer that question.

00:15:40.008 --> 00:15:41.807
Third reason is infection.

00:15:41.807 --> 00:15:44.229
Pathogens evolve faster than we do.

00:15:44.229 --> 00:15:46.122
It's too bad, and it's amazing

00:15:46.122 --> 00:15:48.617
that we can ever, ever outrun them.

00:15:48.617 --> 00:15:50.878
Therefore, it is very strong selection

00:15:50.878 --> 00:15:52.668
to survive whatever kinds of pathogens

00:15:52.668 --> 00:15:54.004
and infections are around,

00:15:54.004 --> 00:15:55.695
but whenever you see a mutation

00:15:55.695 --> 00:15:59.115
that gets selected so
strongly to prevent infection,

00:15:59.115 --> 00:16:00.741
you should look very carefully to see if

00:16:00.741 --> 00:16:03.537
there might be bad side
effects to that gene.

00:16:03.537 --> 00:16:05.553
Turns out that there's lots
of evidence about this.

00:16:05.553 --> 00:16:07.905
A nice recent paper goes
through many of them,

00:16:07.905 --> 00:16:12.148
shows pretty convincingly
that each epidemic shapes

00:16:12.148 --> 00:16:14.929
quite dramatic changes
in allele frequencies,

00:16:14.929 --> 00:16:18.038
and furthermore, it points out that CCR5,

00:16:18.038 --> 00:16:19.932
you get HIV protection if you

00:16:19.932 --> 00:16:21.749
have this particular mutation,

00:16:21.749 --> 00:16:24.104
but you're more vulnerable to West Nile.

00:16:24.104 --> 00:16:25.368
If you have an O blood type,

00:16:25.368 --> 00:16:26.919
you get protection against malaria,

00:16:26.919 --> 00:16:28.996
but you're more vulnerable to cholera.

00:16:28.996 --> 00:16:31.652
We need to think about
good genes and bad genes.

00:16:31.652 --> 00:16:33.565
We need to be thinking about variations

00:16:33.565 --> 00:16:35.737
that have costs and benefits.

00:16:35.737 --> 00:16:37.576
Trade-offs, nothing in
the body is perfect.

00:16:37.576 --> 00:16:38.875
Everything is a trade-off.

00:16:38.875 --> 00:16:40.909
My favorite example is bilirubin.

00:16:40.909 --> 00:16:42.424
Why make bilirubin?

00:16:42.424 --> 00:16:44.113
It's toxic, it turns you yellow.

00:16:44.113 --> 00:16:46.057
Turns out, it's wonderful at stopping

00:16:46.057 --> 00:16:47.526
reactive oxygen species

00:16:47.526 --> 00:16:49.312
from burning up your tissues.

00:16:49.312 --> 00:16:50.926
And people who have a disease

00:16:50.926 --> 00:16:52.356
causing high bilirubin levels

00:16:52.356 --> 00:16:54.746
have heart attacks at
half the rate of others.

00:16:54.746 --> 00:16:56.987
Very important for practical terms

00:16:56.987 --> 00:16:58.231
in a neonatal nursery,

00:16:58.231 --> 00:17:00.105
because they're routinely put under lights

00:17:00.105 --> 00:17:01.793
for even mild increases of bilirubin,

00:17:01.793 --> 00:17:03.898
even though that bilirubin decreases

00:17:03.898 --> 00:17:07.732
the number of reactionary
oxygen species in their bodies.

00:17:07.732 --> 00:17:10.036
Genes for aging, George
Williams pointed out

00:17:10.036 --> 00:17:11.459
a new explanation that is,

00:17:11.459 --> 00:17:13.094
they might have benefits in childhood,

00:17:13.094 --> 00:17:16.929
when selection is strong,
and costs only later in life.

00:17:16.929 --> 00:17:19.907
The so-called Antagonistic
Pleiotropy Theory.

00:17:19.907 --> 00:17:22.101
If, in fact, we could eliminate aging,

00:17:22.101 --> 00:17:24.182
and the mortality rate stayed the same

00:17:24.182 --> 00:17:26.509
throughout life as it is at age 20,

00:17:26.509 --> 00:17:30.240
most of us would live to
about age 800 to 1000.

00:17:30.240 --> 00:17:34.049
Amyloid Beta is the bad guy for
causing Alzheimer's Disease,

00:17:34.049 --> 00:17:35.442
but has demonstrated recently

00:17:35.442 --> 00:17:38.064
that in fact, it's potent antimicrobial.

00:17:38.064 --> 00:17:39.912
Every single one of these genes

00:17:39.912 --> 00:17:41.523
seems like it's just a bad actor,

00:17:41.523 --> 00:17:43.183
but it's there for a reason.

00:17:43.183 --> 00:17:45.324
Not all are, we shouldn't assume it,

00:17:45.324 --> 00:17:47.661
but we should consider the possibilities.

00:17:47.661 --> 00:17:49.838
And Ajit Varki's work, he's shown that

00:17:49.838 --> 00:17:51.772
all human are missing a gene that our

00:17:51.772 --> 00:17:53.832
primate ancestors all had,

00:17:53.832 --> 00:17:55.749
that is one for Neu5Gc,

00:17:57.222 --> 00:17:59.051
and it turns out that two

00:17:59.051 --> 00:18:00.718
or three million years ago we lost it,

00:18:00.718 --> 00:18:03.829
but we keep eating other
foods that have that in it,

00:18:03.829 --> 00:18:08.061
and it may well be that
causes inflammatory reactions,

00:18:08.061 --> 00:18:10.002
which might be responsible for the

00:18:10.002 --> 00:18:14.347
high burden of inflammatory
disease in humans.

00:18:14.347 --> 00:18:16.197
It might be that the reason that happened

00:18:16.197 --> 00:18:19.817
was to help us avoid the kind of malaria

00:18:19.817 --> 00:18:21.744
that influences chimpanzees

00:18:21.744 --> 00:18:23.640
because that molecule is what

00:18:23.640 --> 00:18:27.807
the malaria pathogen uses
to get into blood cells.

00:18:28.839 --> 00:18:32.839
Change can increase
reproduction in harm health,

00:18:33.740 --> 00:18:37.605
Apo E4 increases
progesterone in reproduction,

00:18:37.605 --> 00:18:40.922
even though it causes heart
attacks and Alzheimer's Disease.

00:18:40.922 --> 00:18:43.328
Even the BRCA gene, causing breast cancer,

00:18:43.328 --> 00:18:46.718
has been said to increase
number of offspring.

00:18:46.718 --> 00:18:49.649
And finally, defenses, such as
pain, fever, and all the rest

00:18:49.649 --> 00:18:52.038
are useful but at a high cost.

00:18:52.038 --> 00:18:54.995
Wrapping up, why do disease genes persist?

00:18:54.995 --> 00:18:57.766
The same six categories
that prove so useful

00:18:57.766 --> 00:18:59.657
in trying to understand why certain traits

00:18:59.657 --> 00:19:02.530
are vulnerable to causing disease

00:19:02.530 --> 00:19:05.586
helps us understand genetic variations

00:19:05.586 --> 00:19:07.846
and genetic uniformities in ways

00:19:07.846 --> 00:19:09.821
that make us vulnerable to disease.

00:19:09.821 --> 00:19:11.629
Constraints leave us with mutations

00:19:11.629 --> 00:19:13.906
heterozygote advantage vulnerabilities.

00:19:13.906 --> 00:19:15.867
Mismatched results in quirks

00:19:15.867 --> 00:19:18.301
that were harmless now causing disease.

00:19:18.301 --> 00:19:20.963
Trade-offs come with benefits, but costs.

00:19:20.963 --> 00:19:23.082
Pathogens create arm races.

00:19:23.082 --> 00:19:26.110
Reproduction sometimes
shapes changes in genes

00:19:26.110 --> 00:19:28.378
that increase reproduction
at a cost to health,

00:19:28.378 --> 00:19:30.731
and defenses are dangerous and costly.

00:19:30.731 --> 00:19:32.374
Again, going back to four
different kinds of genes,

00:19:32.374 --> 00:19:34.370
variations among individuals,

00:19:34.370 --> 00:19:36.490
variations among human subgroups,

00:19:36.490 --> 00:19:38.856
recent changes that we all have,

00:19:38.856 --> 00:19:41.780
such as losing the ability
to synthesize Vitamin C,

00:19:41.780 --> 00:19:43.288
and then other things like dopamine,

00:19:43.288 --> 00:19:45.450
that we all have had for a very long time.

00:19:45.450 --> 00:19:47.185
We need to be thinking about all these

00:19:47.185 --> 00:19:49.078
different kinds of genes and their

00:19:49.078 --> 00:19:52.507
ways in which they make us
more vulnerable to disease.

00:19:52.507 --> 00:19:55.053
This exercise of writing
this lecture was fun for me,

00:19:55.053 --> 00:19:56.318
because it came out with surprising

00:19:56.318 --> 00:19:58.152
conclusions I hadn't anticipated.

00:19:58.152 --> 00:20:00.427
First, there's a very high proportion

00:20:00.427 --> 00:20:03.690
of disease vulnerability
genes that are shaped by

00:20:03.690 --> 00:20:06.849
benefits of protecting against infection.

00:20:06.849 --> 00:20:09.232
And, two, they persist
because of selection for

00:20:09.232 --> 00:20:11.331
infection increase in reproduction

00:20:11.331 --> 00:20:13.374
and extending the lifespan.

00:20:13.374 --> 00:20:14.673
Those of you who are interested,

00:20:14.673 --> 00:20:16.663
we now do have a scientific society,

00:20:16.663 --> 00:20:18.357
Evolutionary Medicine, it's called

00:20:18.357 --> 00:20:19.190
The International Society for

00:20:19.190 --> 00:20:20.953
Evolution Medicine and Public Health.

00:20:20.953 --> 00:20:22.261
We have a meeting in Europe

00:20:22.261 --> 00:20:24.284
that you'd be welcome to go.

00:20:24.284 --> 00:20:27.326
EvMedEd is a resource, and EvMedReview.com

00:20:27.326 --> 00:20:28.904
offers news for the field,

00:20:28.904 --> 00:20:31.025
including right now a meeting that's open

00:20:31.025 --> 00:20:32.558
for anyone who wants to attend,

00:20:32.558 --> 00:20:33.797
November 10th in Berlin,

